<!-- ===================== VALUES ===================== -->
<section class="values-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="row g-5 align-items-start">
      <div class="col-lg-5">
        <h2 class="section-headline">The Beamer Wizard standard.</h2>
        <p class="section-sub">
          The credential means something because it represents <strong>a set of values, not just a
          skill set</strong>. Verified Beamer Wizards commit to the following.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-6 offset-lg-1">
        <div class="value-item">
          <div class="value-icon">🔓</div>
          <div>
            <h3>No vendor lock-in</h3>
            <p>Clients are guided toward <strong>solutions they own</strong>. When a platform that creates lock-in is unavoidable, the Wizard <strong>explains the trade-off clearly</strong> before work begins.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="value-item">
          <div class="value-icon">🎓</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Self-sufficiency is the goal</h3>
            <p>Every engagement ends with <strong>the client more capable</strong> than when they started. <strong>Teaching is the product.</strong> Neither side wants dependency.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="value-item">
          <div class="value-icon">🌿</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Open source principles</h3>
            <p>Wizards build on <strong>open foundations</strong> where possible. <strong>Transparency, portability, and avoiding proprietary lock-in</strong> are not optional extras.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="value-item">
          <div class="value-icon">🔧</div>
          <div>
            <h3>Version control fluency</h3>
            <p><strong>Git is a baseline expectation</strong>, not a bonus skill. Beamer Wizards understand CI/CD and build with <strong>good practices from the start</strong>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

